  "text": "Identified all key files for DSL-to-Processor-API migration in apache/kafka. The architecture has three layers:\n\n**DSL Interfaces** (public API): `KStream.java`, `KTable.java`, `KGroupedStream.java`, `KGroupedTable.java` \u2014 define DSL operations like map(), filter(), groupBy(), aggregate(), reduce().\n\n**DSL Internal Implementations**: `KStreamImpl.java` and `KTableImpl.java` implement the DSL interfaces and wire DSL calls to internal processor suppliers. `KGroupedStreamImpl.java` and `KGroupedTableImpl.java` handle groupBy results and aggregate/reduce operations.\n\n**DSL Operation Processors** (the bridge): Each DSL operation has a corresponding ProcessorSupplier implementation that creates Processor instances:\n- `KStreamMap` \u2192 implements `ProcessorSupplier<KIn,VIn,KOut,VOut>` (key-changing map, uses `ContextualProcessor`)\n- `KStreamMapValues` \u2192 implements `FixedKeyProcessorSupplier` (value-only map, uses `ContextualFixedKeyProcessor`)\n- `KStreamFilter` \u2192 implements `FixedKeyProcessorSupplier` (filter, uses `ContextualFixedKeyProcessor`)\n- `KStreamFlatMap` \u2192 implements `ProcessorSupplier` (flatMap)\n- `KStreamFlatMapValues` \u2192 implements `FixedKeyProcessorSupplier` (flatMapValues)\n- `KStreamAggregate` / `KStreamReduce` \u2192 stateful processors using `KeyValueStoreWrapper` for state store management\n- `KTableFilter`, `KTableMapValues`, `KTableAggregate`, `KTableReduce` \u2192 implement `KTableProcessorSupplier` (which extends `ProcessorSupplier`) with state store integration\n- `KTableRepartitionMap` \u2192 internal repartitioning for keyed aggregations\n\n**Processor API** (target for migration): `Processor.java`, `FixedKeyProcessor.java`, `ProcessorSupplier.java`, `FixedKeyProcessorSupplier.java`, `ProcessorContext.java`, `FixedKeyProcessorContext.java`, `ContextualProcessor.java`, `ContextualFixedKeyProcessor.java` \u2014 the low-level API. `StateStore.java` for custom state stores. `Topology.java` for manually wiring processors.\n\nKey insight: DSL operations internally already implement the Processor API. For migration, developers can study these internal implementations to understand exactly how each DSL operation maps to processor logic, then replicate/customize that logic with direct state store access via `ProcessorContext.getStateStore()`.",
